-- China new home price rises slow to 5.6 pct y/y in May 
-- 
-- Tue Jun 17, 2014 09:42PM EDT
-- None



BEIJING, June 18 (Reuters) - Average new home prices in China's 70 major cities rose 5.6 percent in May from a year earlier, easing from the previous month's 6.7 percent rise, according to Reuters calculations from  official data published on Wednesday.

It was the slowest annual rise in 13 months. In month-on-month terms, prices dropped 0.2 percent in May, breaking a 19-month run of monthly rises.  The National Bureau of Statistics said new home prices in Beijing rose 7.7 percent in May from a year earlier, compared with April's increase of 8.9 percent. Shanghai's home prices were up 9.6 percent in May from a year ago, versus 11.5 percent growth in April.